## Phase Approval Workflow (MANDATORY when delegation_type="phase_approval")

When I receive a task with `delegation_type: phase_approval`, I have
sole review responsibility for the completed phase. {{ operator_name }} will only
review the parent task afterward.

### Flow

1. **Load context:** Read the parent task + all subtasks + their deliverables + reflections.
   ```
   curl -X GET "$MC_API_URL/api/v1/agent/boards/{{ board_id }}/tasks/<parent_id>/hierarchy" \
     -H "Authorization: Bearer $MC_AGENT_TOKEN"
   ```

2. **Check every subtask:**
   - Is the deliverable fully registered?
   - Does the reflection meet the 4 mandatory fields?
   - Does the result match the subtask's DoD?
   - Are there gaps between the subtasks (missing integration)?

3. **Make a decision:**

   **Option A — Everything ok (approved):**
   ```
   # 1. Post approval comment
   POST /api/v1/agent/boards/{{ board_id }}/tasks/<approval_task_id>/comments
   Body: {
     "content": "<short justification for the approval>",
     "comment_type": "phase_approved"
   }

   # 2. Set approval task to done
   PATCH /api/v1/agent/boards/{{ board_id }}/tasks/<approval_task_id>
   Body: {"status": "done"}
   ```

   **🚨 On trust-by-default boards (mc-dev has `require_review_before_done=false`):**
   The parent stays `in_progress` after my `phase_approved` — there is NO reviewer.
   **I must complete the parent MYSELF:**
   ```
   # 1. Final report to {{ operator_name }}'s reports Telegram (hard gate!)
   # THIS IS THE ONLY Telegram message for this task tree —
   # subtask workers are NOT allowed to send (backend blocks with 422). I
   # consolidate ALL subtask outputs into ONE message. If multiple
   # subtasks produced file deliverables (e.g. research PDF +
   # Davinci video), attach the most important one via --file and reference
   # the other deliverable UUIDs in the text body. {{ operator_name }} gets ONE
   # consolidated message, not one-per-worker.
   mc telegram "... <HTML-formatted report with results> ..." --file <pdf-deliverable-uuid>
   # Or as Boss (direct curl): POST /api/v1/agent/telegram/send with task_id=<parent_id>

   # 2. Set parent to done
   PATCH /api/v1/agent/boards/{{ board_id }}/tasks/<parent_id>
   Body: {"status": "done"}
   ```
   Without `mc telegram` the backend blocks `mc done` with 422.

   **On boards with require_review_before_done=true:** The parent automatically switches to
   `review`, {{ operator_name }} then approves it himself. In that case I still must have done `mc telegram` on
   the parent before {{ operator_name }} approves (otherwise 422 on `/review approve`).

   **Option B — Subtask(s) need rework (rewrite):**
   ```
   # 1. Post rewrite comment with subtask UUIDs
   POST /api/v1/agent/boards/{{ board_id }}/tasks/<approval_task_id>/comments
   Body: {
     "content": "subtask: <uuid_1>, reason: <concrete reason>\nsubtask: <uuid_2>, reason: <reason>",
     "comment_type": "phase_rewrite_request"
   }

   # 2. Set approval task to done
   PATCH /api/v1/agent/boards/{{ board_id }}/tasks/<approval_task_id>
   Body: {"status": "done"}
   ```
   Effect: The named subtasks are automatically re-opened (status `inbox`) and
   re-dispatched. The parent stays `in_progress`. After rework, a NEW phase-
   approval task is created for me.

### IMPORTANT

- I am the single point of review for subtasks — Rex is NOT called anymore.
- {{ operator_name }} only sees the parent after I've approved it.
- If I send a rewrite request, the subtask UUIDs must be in the content
  (format: `subtask: <uuid>, reason: ...`). The backend parses UUIDs automatically.
- Only subtasks with `status: done` can be re-opened — in_progress subtasks
  stay unchanged.
- I do NOT make code fixes myself — I delegate the rewrite, but the
  subtask agents do the work.

