### Delegation vs Briefing vs Note — which call, when?

Three scenarios, three different calls. Mixing them up = worker gets nothing and the task stalls (live bug 2026-05-13, bug memo #9):

| Scenario | Call | Effect |
|---|---|---|
| **New sub-task for a worker** (worker should do something concrete that doesn't exist yet) | `mc delegate "..." --to <agent> --description "..."` | Creates a new sub-task with its own dispatch → worker gets the prompt in their session. My task → `blocked` with callback. |
| **Briefing / wake signal on an already-assigned task** (sub-task exists, worker is `assigned_agent_id`, I'm giving them additional instructions or nudging them) | `mc comment handoff "<text>"` (task_id from active context) | `handoff` is a **deliverable** comment_type → worker sees it via `/me/poll` and wakes up. |
| **Routine note / audit entry** (status update for {{ operator_name }}, context note for myself, no call to a worker) | `mc comment message "<text>"` (default — task_id from active context) | Stays in the audit log. Is **not** delivered to another agent. |

**Forbidden:** `mc comment message "Briefing text for worker XYZ"` on someone else's assigned task. The worker will never see it — the system responds with a `delivery_hint` in the response, don't ignore it. Instead use `mc comment handoff "..."` (existing task) or `mc delegate` (new task).

Correct flow — root task + child task for Boss:
```
{{ operator_name }}: "Take a screenshot of the login page"

Step 1: Create a ROOT TASK for myself (I keep ownership of the request):
POST /api/v1/agent/boards/{{ board_id }}/tasks
{
  "title": "Screenshot Login-Seite fuer {{ operator_name }}",
  "description": "{{ operator_name }} moechte einen Screenshot der Login-Seite.",
  "assigned_agent_id": "{{ agent_id }}",
  "report_back_required": true,
  "report_back_channel": "telegram",
  "report_back_chat_id": "{{ telegram_chat_id }}",
  "report_back_requirements": "screenshot",
  "requester_channel": "telegram",
  "requester_id": "{{ telegram_chat_id }}"
}
→ I get back root_task_id

Step 2: Create a CHILD TASK for Boss (Boss orchestrates the rest):
POST /api/v1/agent/boards/{{ board_id }}/tasks
{
  "title": "Screenshot von localhost/login erstellen",
  "description": "[full context: goal, stack, DoD, branch, paths, credentials]",
  "parent_task_id": "<root_task_id>",
  "assigned_agent_id": "<boss_agent_id>"
}

Step 3: Wait until Boss is done
→ The system notifies me automatically once all children are done
→ I read the result from Boss's child-task comments
→ I reply to {{ operator_name }} with the result
→ I set the root task to done
```

