## Visual Tests via Playwright MCP (MANDATORY for screenshot/modal/visual tasks)

**Architecture since 2026-04-23:** Visual tests run via the Playwright MCP server
(microsoft/playwright-mcp). You use MCP tools directly — screenshots come back
**inline as image content in the tool response**, so your LLM sees them
immediately. No more "blind" verification via JSON paths.

**Available MCP tools** (all as `mcp__playwright__browser_*`):
- `browser_navigate(url)` — open a page
- `browser_snapshot()` — accessibility tree with element refs (for targeting)
- `browser_take_screenshot(filename?)` — image returned inline (THIS is what you see!)
- `browser_fill_form(fields)` — multiple fields in one call
- `browser_click(element_ref)` — click via ref from snapshot
- `browser_type(element_ref, text)` — type text into a field
- `browser_evaluate(function)` — run JS in the browser
- `browser_wait_for(text|time)` — until text is visible / time elapses
- `browser_close()` — end the browser session

**The browser session is STATEFUL** — everything stays in the same browser context until
`browser_close`. Log in once → many further actions without re-login.

### Default flow: viewing a simple page

```
1. browser_navigate(url="http://caddy/some-page")
2. browser_take_screenshot(filename="<TASK_ID>/some-page.png")
   → You see the image immediately INLINE in the tool response.
   → File lands at /shared-mcp/<TASK_ID>/some-page.png (also visible to {{ operator_name }} in the UI)
3. browser_close()
4. In the comment: describe concretely what's visible
5. Register as a deliverable so {{ operator_name }} sees the image in the UI:
   mc deliverable --type screenshot --title "Some Page" --path /shared-mcp/<TASK_ID>/some-page.png
```

**IMPORTANT — filename convention:** `browser_take_screenshot(filename="<TASK_ID>/<descriptive-name>.png")`.
The `<TASK_ID>/` subdir is mandatory — it prevents collisions when multiple agents
screenshot simultaneously. Backend rejects the deliverable with 422 if the path
doesn't match `/shared-mcp/<TASK_ID>/`.

### Logged-in state via vault credential

```
1. Find the credential UUID:
   curl -s http://caddy/api/v1/agent/boards/<board_id>/credentials \
     -H "Authorization: Bearer $MC_AGENT_TOKEN" \
     | jq '.[] | select(.credential_type=="login") | {id, name, url}'

   Tip: for MC UI tests there is usually "MC Login for Tests".
   For a new project: ask {{ operator_name }} which credential can be used.

2. Fetch the credential data (decrypted):
   curl -s http://caddy/api/v1/agent/boards/<board_id>/credentials/<cred-uuid> \
     -H "Authorization: Bearer $MC_AGENT_TOKEN"
   → returns {data: {username, password}, url: "http://caddy/login"}

3. Log in via MCP:
   browser_navigate(url="http://caddy/login")
   browser_snapshot()  → gives you the form element refs
   browser_fill_form([
     {ref: "<email-ref>", value: "<username from cred>"},
     {ref: "<password-ref>", value: "<password from cred>"}
   ])
   browser_click(element_ref="<submit-button-ref>")
   browser_wait_for(text_gone="Log in")  # or text="Expected UI text after login"

4. Navigate to the target page + screenshot:
   browser_navigate(url="http://caddy/tasks")
   browser_take_screenshot(filename="<TASK_ID>/tasks-logged-in.png")
   → you see it inline + it lands at /shared-mcp/<TASK_ID>/tasks-logged-in.png

5. browser_close()

6. Register as a deliverable (otherwise {{ operator_name }} won't see the image in the UI):
   mc deliverable --type screenshot --title "tasks page (logged in)" \
                  --path /shared-mcp/tasks-logged-in.png
   → mc deliverable auto-copies the file to /deliverables/<task_id>/ (auto-copy
     magic, returns the deliverable ID — you'll need that in a moment for mc telegram).

7. Send the image to {{ operator_name }} via Telegram (a real photo, not just text):
   mc telegram "Caption describing what's visible" --photo <deliverable-id>
   → Backend uses sendPhoto instead of sendMessage. Caption is limited to 1024
     characters (Telegram limit). Text gets truncated if too long.
```

**Practical note:** `--path` can be flat (`/shared-mcp/foo.png`) — mc deliverable
takes care of creating the subdir under `/deliverables/<task_id>/`. You do NOT need to
mkdir yourself (the `/shared-mcp/` mount is read-only).

### Modal/click workflow

```
browser_navigate(url="http://caddy/")
browser_snapshot()  → refs of all visible elements
browser_click(element_ref="<new-order-button-ref>")
browser_wait_for(text="Expected modal header")
browser_take_screenshot()  → modal visible
```

### 🔴 HARD GATE — Visual Self-Check (UNCHANGED)

**You now SEE the screenshots inline.** Forbidden phrases without an image-content quote:
- "Page loaded" / "Login worked" / "All clean"

**Mandatory in the task comment:** describe concretely what's visible in the screenshot
(sidebar items, header, table columns, user avatar, etc.).

For login tests, EXPLICITLY check whether the image shows a login form
(email/password fields + "Log in" button) → **login failed, BLOCK the
task**, don't report "ok".

### Legacy: `mc verify` (DEPRECATED for agent workflows)

`mc verify` still exists for **reporting use cases** (e.g. pre-deploy
performance snapshot with automatic Telegram report). For agent-driven
UI tests, **use Playwright MCP** (see above). Rationale:
mc verify returned JSON paths, you had to call Read separately, and often
didn't visually verify screenshots (hallucination bug 2026-04-23).
With MCP you see the image directly.

If someone explicitly requests "performance report for {{ operator_name }}": yes, then use mc verify.
Otherwise: Playwright MCP.

